  "response": "Stars are primarily made of **hydrogen** and **helium**. These two elements make up the vast majority of a star's mass. There are also trace amounts of heavier elements present, which astronomers collectively refer to as \"metals,\" even though they aren't all metals in the chemical sense.\n\nHere's a more detailed breakdown:\n\n*   **Hydrogen (H):** Usually around 70-75% of a star's mass. This is the fuel that powers stars through nuclear fusion.\n*   **Helium (He):** Usually around 25-30% of a star's mass. It's a byproduct of hydrogen fusion.\n*   **\"Metals\":** A very small percentage (ranging from less than 1% to a few percent), but important. These include elements like oxygen, carbon, nitrogen, iron, neon, silicon, magnesium, sulfur, and others. The specific abundance of these elements can vary depending on the star's age and where it was born in the galaxy.\n\nDuring a star's life, the composition changes as it fuses lighter elements into heavier ones in its core.\n",
